title: For Sale/Trade:  Glock 19 Gen 2 **Polished Stainless Slide**
postcontent:
Glock 19 Gen 2 with polished Stainless slide.  This gun is in excellent condition and comes with 2 magazines, a Phobus paddle holster and at full price I will include 100 rounds of 9mm ammo with it.

If you've never owned a Glock, you've certainly heard of their rock solid reputation for reliability.  I personally prefer the Gen 2 as the finger grooves of the Gen 3 and Gen 4 models don't fit my hand well and feel out of place, and I don't exactly have big hands.

I've had numerous questions about the slide being polished and whether it affects the corrosion resistance or not.  The short answer is "no", it does not.  Glock goes through a two stage finishing process.  The first stage is the "Tenifer" coating which is the corrosion resistance coating.  The second stage is the black "Parkerizing" coating.  The polish process is simply removing that outer Parkerized coating to reveal the beautiful Tenifer coating underneath.  The Tenifer coating still retains all of the corrosion resistance properties and in fact is more reliable than aftermarket coatings.

Here's the longer answer via the Glock WIKI page:
"The barrel and slide undergo two hardening processes prior to treatment with a proprietary nitriding process called Tenifer. The Tenifer treatment is applied in a 500 °C nitrate bath.[36] The Tenifer finish is between 0.04 mm (0.0016 in) and 0.05 mm (0.0020 in) in thickness, and is characterized by extreme resistance to wear and corrosion; it penetrates the metal, and treated parts have similar properties even below the surface to a certain depth.[38]
The Tenifer process produces a matte gray-colored, non-glare surface with a 64 Rockwell C hardness rating and a 99% resistance to salt water corrosion (which meets or exceeds stainless steel specifications),[37] making the Glock particularly suitable for individuals carrying the pistol concealed as the highly chloride-resistant finish allows the pistol to better endure the effects of perspiration.[38] Glock steel parts having the Tenifer treatment are more corrosion-resistant than analogous gun parts having other finishes or treatments, including Teflon, bluing, hard chrome plating, or phosphates.[38] After applying the Tenifer process, a black Parkerized decorative surface finish is applied. The underlaying Tenifer treatment will remain protecting these parts even if the decorative surface finish were to wear off.[9]"

Thanks for looking!!
